**Abstract:**
Major essay titled "On Written and Spoken Language" critiquing both Searle's speech-act theory and Derridean deconstruction. Opens with Gilson-de Lubac correspondence on scholastic rationalism. Argues Searle wrongly takes written language as model, reducing all understanding to "illocutionary effects." Contends spoken language is primary, that statements aim at conduct-in-response not mere understanding, and that the distinction between illocutionary and perlocutionary effects is illegitimate. Critiques deconstructionists for applying their critique only to written texts.

**AI Recommendation:** Major theoretical essay; variant of 98-APR-1. Continues to 98-APR-2.

